17.body: Docker is a platform that enables developers to automate the deployment of applications inside lightweight, portable containers. Containers allow applications and their dependencies to be packaged together, ensuring consistency across different environments.
17.title: 1. Introduction

20.body: Install Docker Compose by following the instructions in the official documentation .
20.title: 2.2. Docker Compose

21.body: Verify your Docker installation by running docker --version and docker-compose --version. Run a simple container: docker run hello-world.
21.title: 3. Getting Started

23.body: List images: docker images Pull an image: docker pull image_name:tag Remove an image: docker rmi image_name:tag
23.title: 4.1. Images

24.body: List running containers: docker ps List all containers (including stopped): docker ps -a Run a container: docker run image_name Stop a running container: docker stop container_id Remove a container: docker rm container_id
24.title: 4.2. Containers

25.body: List networks: docker network ls Create a network: docker network create network_name
25.title: 4.3. Networking

26.body: List volumes: docker volume ls Create a volume: docker volume create volume_name
26.title: 4.4. Volumes

27.body: Create a Dockerfile to define the image configuration. Example Dockerfile: FROM base_image:tag WORKDIR /app COPY . . RUN npm install CMD ["npm", "start"]
27.title: 5. Dockerfile

28.body:
Define multi-container applications using a docker-compose.yml file. Example docker-compose.yml: version: '3'
services: web: image: nginx:latest ports: - "8080:80" app: build: . ports: - "3000:3000"
28.title: 6. Docker Compose

29.body: Docker Swarm allows you to create and manage a cluster of Docker nodes. Initialize a Swarm: docker swarm init

30.body: Keep images small. Use multi-stage builds. Optimize Dockerfile layers. Use .dockerignore to exclude unnecessary files. Avoid running processes as root in containers.

31.body: Check container logs: docker logs container_id. Use docker exec -it container_id /bin/bash to access a container's shell. Check the Docker documentation and community forums for assistance.
